article.description:
Michael Olowokandi scored 23 points, and
Elton Brand had 18 points and 10 rebounds as the Los Angeles
Clippers beat the Denver Nuggets 97-75 Sunday night to snap a
three-game losing streak.
article.headline: Clippers end three-game losing streak
article.linkText: Clippers remain in playoff hunt with rout
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Having spoken out about his contract situation and gotten fined, Michael Olowokandi showed the Los Angeles Clippers why they'd do well to keep him around.
Olowokandi

Olowokandi had 23 points, six rebounds and six blocked shots as the Clippers beat the Denver Nuggets 97-75 Sunday night to snap a three-game losing streak. The Clippers fined Olowokandi $50,000 on Friday, saying his comments after the team's loss to Utah on Wednesday were detrimental to the team. Among other things, Olowokandi said, "Things are very uncertain with the future of this team. It's starting to affect the way we play the game." Olowokandi spoke to general manager Elgin Baylor on Sunday. "The fine hurt somewhat, but probably the most disappointing thing for me was the reason that they gave," Olowokandi said. "I've never, ever been detrimental to this team. What I said, maybe it was out of line. I was frustrated. Maybe I could have handled it a little bit differently, but I felt I was doing it for the sake of the team." Olowokandi is eligible to become a free agent this summer and point guard Jeff McInnis is eligible to become an unrestricted free agent. Several others, including power forward Elton Brand, are eligible for long-term contract extensions. Whether owner Donald Sterling comes up with the money to keep the team together remains to be seen. "I guess you have to take the positive out of any negative, and the positive is we did play as a team," Olowokandi said. "We chose not to worry about all those other things. Those are things that will be dealt with when the time comes." Los Angeles' Brand had 18 points and 10 rebounds. His four offensive rebounds broke the single-season franchise record of 371 set by Michael Cage in 1987-88. Brand's 54th double-double tied Sven Nater's club record set in 1980-81. "Individual accolades are great, but I'd rather trade them for a playoff run," Brand said. The Clippers are close to being eliminated from playoff contention -- they trail eighth-place Utah by 4½ games with five remaining in the race for the final postseason spot in the Western Conference. However, Los Angeles moved within a game of getting back to .500 with a 38-39 record. "For us to stick to our goal to at least be .500 is important for us," Brand said. James Posey scored 18 points to lead the Nuggets, who have lost three straight on the road and 14 of their last 16. Donnell Harvey added 16 points, including Denver's final 10 of the game. Although the Nuggets are out of playoff contention, Posey said there's still something to play for. "Every game means something. You've got to play as hard as you can, get as much from yourself as possible," he said. "I just play every game like it's my last. You never know, it could be your last." Reserve guard Quentin Richardson sparked the Clippers with 22 points. He scored 14 in a row bridging the end of the third quarter and the start of the fourth, when the Clippers led by 27 points. "I started getting open and got a chance to knock some shots down," Richardson said. "Once you get a few shots, everything becomes easy for you." Except for an early tie, Los Angeles led all the way. The Clippers shot 58 percent in the first quarter and led by 10. They were ahead by 16 at halftime. Denver got within 13 on a 3-pointer by Posey with 4:12 left in the third quarter. "We played with no energy. We were out of gas," Nuggets coach Mike Evans said." Richardson had seven points as the Clippers outscored Denver 13-2 the rest of the period for a 74-50 lead going into the final quarter. Richardson kept it up in the fourth, scoring 12 of the Clippers' first 17 points for a 91-63 lead with 4:30 to play. Game notes
McInnis had 13 assists for the Clippers. ... The Nuggets have lost four in a row to the Clippers in Los Angeles. The Clippers won the season series 3-1. ... Denver is 6-46 this season when giving up at least 94 points. ... A crowd of 18,964 gave the Clippers their 13th consecutive sellout and 22nd of the season at Staples Center. They've already more than doubled last season's club record of 11 sellouts.
